      "https://drive.google.com/file/d/1fSHo3WZbEjAujHTnPyN2UxkJplo58DKk/preview",
    songTitle: "Thirupadagam Thannil",
    songURL:
      "https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/1438809322&color=%23b4e8e8&auto_play=false&hide_related=true&show_comments=false&show_user=true&show_reposts=false&show_teaser=false",
    songRagam: "Karaharapriya",
    songThalam: "Misra Chaapu",
    songIntro:
      "<span><p>Welcome to our musical journey to 48th Divyadesam Thiruppadagam located in Periya Kancheepuram near Gangaikondan mandapam. Moolavr is Pandava Thoothan with a sitting posture facing east.</p><p>During the period of Mahabharatha Lord Krishna when visited Hasthinapura to meet Kauravas as Pandava Thoothan he was tried to be trapped by Duriodhana through seating on a chair arranged on a false platform made of dried grass so that when he sat on it he was taken down to the basement of the palace where he had to fight with wrestlers who were ready to kill him. After conquering them Krishna showed his giagantic swaroop vishwaroopam to Kauravas including Dhritarashtra the blind king and father of Duriyodhana. When Krishna offered a boon to Dhritarashtra he requested Krishna to make him again blind as he didn't want to see any other thing after the Dharshan of vishwaroopam of Lord Krishna.</p><p>After hundreds of years of Mahabharatha war the King Jename jeyan who was the great grand son of Pandavas wanted to see the vishwaroopam of Pandava Thoothan his guru Rishi Vaisambayanar advised him to go to Kancheepuram and perform aswamedha yaagam and pray to Lord Vishnu. He did accordingly and upon hearing his prayer Lord Krishna showed him his Vishwaroopam as Pandava Thoothan at this sthalam.</p><p>One can see such a big deity (25feet tall) in a sitting posture only in this shrine. Thaayaar Rukmini and Sathya bama. Pada means Big; Agam means Residence signifying Thiruppadagam as the place where Lord Mahavishnu resides with his great form.</p><p>Peyaazhwaar Bhoothathaazhwar Thirumazhisai aazhwaar and ThirumangaiAazhwaar worshipped this shrine and sang paasurams in praise of this deity.</p><p>Adiyen composed a Krithi on Pandava Thoothan of Thiruppadagam and tuned it in the raagam Karaharapriya. Singers are Dr.Thatham and Mrs.Amutha. Please listen and enjoy.</p></span>",
