      "<span><p>The 60th Divya Desam towards which are proceeding our musical journey is திருவல்லிக்கேணி. The temple is a 6th century one located near the sea shore of Bay of Bengal in Chennai. This shrine was reported in Brahmanda purana as forest with a dense population of holy herb Thulasi.</p><p>Once a king named Sumathi was praying to Lord Venkatesha at Thirumala to show his appearance of Partha Sarathi to him. Lord Venkatesha directed him to go to this place and see that. On that direction the king reached here and saw the Partha Sarathi roopa of Lord Vishnu. That is why the lord here is known as Venkata Krishna meaning the Krishna shown by Venkatesha of Thirumala to his devotee King Sumathi. The presiding deity in the main Sanctum sanctorum is Lord Krishna in a standing posture with his characteristic mustache as he was the driver (sarathy) of the chariot of Partha (Arjuna).</p><p>In this Sanctum sanctorum itself in addition to Lord Krishna five other deities are also seen. They are Rukmini Thaayaar, Balaraman (elder brother of Krishna), Saathyagi (a great Yaadhava warrior devoted to Kishna and who took training in shooting arrows under Dhrona along with Arjuna during their early days of schooling), Pradyumna (eldest son of Krishna and Rukmini), Aniruddha son of Pradyumna (grand son of Krishna). The urchavar is Partha Sarathi with characteristic hit impressions of arrows on his face at Kurukshetra. In addition to these presiding deities four other forms of Lord Vishnu are seen in 4 different Sanctums. They are Lord Narasimha ( as per the prayers of sage Atthiri), Lord Rama (as per the prayers of Madhuman Rishi), Lord Gajendra varadhar (as per the prayers of Saint Saptharomar), Lord Renganathan (as per the wishes of Vadavalli Thaayaar). This shrine was praised by PeyAazhwaar, Thirumazhisai Aazhvaar and Thirumangai aazhwaar in Divyaprabandham.</p><p>Adiyen composed a krithi on Venkata Krishnan of Thiruvallikeni tuned to the raagam கலாவதி. Singers are Dr.Thatham and Mrs.Amutha. Please listen and enjoy.</p></span>",
