    songRagam: "Gowlai",
    songThalam: "Aadi",
    songIntro:
      "<span><p>We are now proceeding to 62nd Divya Desam திருவிடவெந்தை என்னும் திருஇடஎந்தை through our musical journey. This Divya Desam is situated near Kovalam on the route of Chennai to Mahabalipuram at a distance of about 12 miles from Mahabalipuram. This sthalam is mentioned in Varahapuranam.</p><p>During Krutha Yuga Lord Narayana appeared as Varaha roopi before king Bali for his thapa at this place and this place was known as Vamakavipuri or Varahapuri. In yet another time one Rishi Kalava (based on the request of Saint Naradha) married a rishi daughter called Kuni and they gave birth to 365 daughters who were the incarnation of goddess Lakshmi. When they were trying to get their daughters married a few saints who came from Varahapuri asked them to go there and pray Varaha for the early marriage. Kalavarishi reached Varahapuri and performed thapa. Lord Varaha came there as a bachelor and told him that he had returned after Divyadesa pilgrimage tour. Kalavarishi requested him to marry his 365 daughters. The man replied that he will marry them one by one every day during the year. On the last day he made all the 365 brides in to one roopa called Akilavalli and held her on his left thigh and took Varaha roopa. As the mahalakshmi is on the left side of Varaha he is known as Thiru Ida Enthai.</p><p>Urchavar is known by the name Nithya kalyana perumal. The name of the first lakshmi (first daughter of Kalavarishi) who married the lord on the first day was Komalavalli. She has a separate sannidhi as a paraellal presiding deity. Many prospective bachelor boys and girls who come to this shrine and pray for early marriage and happy married life. Their requests are fulfilled by this Lord and after marriage they again visit the temple and offer their thanks and gratitude to the lord for His blessings. The Varahamurthy in this shrine was praised by Thirumangai aazhwaar in 13 paasurams.</p><p>Adiyen composed a krithi on this shrine and tuned to raagam Gowlai. Singers are Dr.Thatham and Mrs.Amutha. Please listen and enjoy.</p></span>",
